<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-818-194  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 818 194.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  August 23 1990 n1228 p46(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Shifting times make it hard for operators.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Whyte, Gemma.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Working out problems with data processing personnel is difficultwith shift times, even though the growth of technology may benefita company.andP;  For example, Svenska, a Swedish bank in London, runsmany DP operations with operators working three shifts during a 24hour period.andP;  Operators are required to work up to 20 hours oneweekend in four.andP;  However, if operators get sick, other operatorsare pressured to come in on their standby weekend as well.andP;  Thebank finds it too expensive to pay contractors to do these shifts,and too expensive to pay their workers overtime as well.andP;  Theshift problem is one which needs an alternative.andP;  A worker's bodynever gets a chance to adjust to working different shifts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data ProcessingWork EnvironmentEmployeePersonnel ManagementPersonnel ProblemsCostWork Hours.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>